prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: The expected line with of our targets is 200-600 km/s. As we aim to resolve the line profiles we aim for a velocity resolution of 50-100 km/s depending on the source FWHM and signal to noise ratio. As we aim to cover the full 3mm band we aks for the 1.875MHz bandwidth. To keep the data rates as low as possible we, but still be able to resolve the lines in case of narrow (~200 km/s) lines, we aim for a spectral bining of x 16. The data will be binned to lower resolution depending on the targets FWHM and signal to noise ratio.

Our targets have expectedsource sizes of 1-1.5''. As we only aim to measure the spatially integrated line intensities we aim for the most compact array configurations (C36-1 or C36-2) in order to keep the phase stability at a maximum.

We have used the dust mass estimates of da Cunha et al (2015) together with reasonable assumptions on the gas to dust mass ratio (150) and the Xco=0.8 to estimate the CO(1-0) line luminosity. The intensity estimate of the high-J transitions was done using average CO SEDs of SMGs (Bothwell et al. 2012, Spilker et al. 2014). Based on this calculation we estimate that our targets will have Sco>2.5$mJy and Sco>1.5mJy for most of the fainter sources in our 4 fields with multiple SMGs. This drives or sensitivity request for an rms of 0.5mJy @ 75 \kms\ resolution. We excect typical line width of 400 km/s. The relatively high velocity resolution used for the time estimate will allow us to resolve the CO line profiles and will give us enough margin for velocity binning to even detect the fainter galaxies in the multiple fields.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: The ECDFS is one of the best studied cosmological deep fields. Through a 10 year effort, we have uniquely characterized the submillimeter galaxy (SMG) population in this field through single dish mapping and ALMA follow-up. However, despite our very significant (many 100s of hours) efforts with world's leading optical instrumentation (VLT, Keck, Gemini), we could only determine robust redshifts for ~30% of the SMGs. This unsatisfactory situation can be changed with ALMA, where we can now exploit another route to obtain SMG redshifts, through employing CO line scans. Here we target specifically those sources that have been missed in all spectroscopic follow-up studies in cosmological deep-fields. Combined with our ongoing ALMA efforts to detect [CII] in these SMGs, our proposed observations have the promise to double the completeness of the redshift distribution of unbiased samples of SMGs, a critical step towards addressing the contribution of obscured SF to the total SFRD, 3-D clustering and the triggering mechanism of SMGs.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Cosmology and the High Redshift Universe
